A fort in Nubia. 3D diorama. At certain times the Egyptians built forts like this throughout the south of Egypt and in Nubia. This meant they could control people travelling along the Nile and in the desert beside it. The fort was built with mud brick with stone foundations. Diorama made by R.T. Roussel. 1949.

Kay Gyroplane G-ACVA.  Designed by David Kay and built by Oddie, Bradbury and Cull Limited of Southampton.  Owned by the Glasgow Museum of Transport but is on display at National Museum of Scotland in Edinburgh. G-ACVA, first flew on 18 February 1935. Following the last flight of G-ACVA on 16 August 1947 at Perth Airport (Scotland) at Scone, it was stored there for many years. It was then refurbished at Scone in 1967 and presented to the Museum of Transport, Glasgow.

3D. Requires Red-Cyan glasses. Skull and jawbone of an adult male sperm whale Physeter catodon. This sperm whale over 15 metres long and weighing nearly 40 tonnes was beached on a mudbank in the  Firth of Forth on Easter Monday 1997. He was the first sperm whale to be stranded in the Firth since 1769. The bone at the back of the skull shows signs of disease, but it is likely that the whale died from septicaemia, the result of a long standing injury. This may also explain why he was so far from his usual hunting range in the Atlantic Ocean. It took several weeks for the museum staff to clean the bones and the skeleton is now part of the marine mammal research collection of National Museums Scotland.
